<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0445">
<l>oṉpā ṉokaramicait takara moṟṟu</l>
<l>muntai yoṟṟē ṇakāra miraṭṭum</l>
<l>paḵteṉ kiḷavi yāytapaka raṅkeṭa</l>
<l>niṟṟal vēṇṭu mūkārak kiḷavi</l>
<l>yoṟṟiya takaram ṟakara mākum</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The sound <foreign xml:lang="ta">t</foreign> will combine with the sound <foreign xml:lang="ta">o</foreign> of <foreign xml:lang="ta">oṉpāṉ,</foreign> the con-</l>
<l>sonant succeeding [<foreign xml:lang="ta">o</foreign>] will become double <foreign xml:lang="ta">ṇṇ,</foreign> the <foreign xml:lang="ta">āytam</foreign> and the</l>
<l>sound <foreign xml:lang="ta">pa</foreign> of the word <foreign xml:lang="ta">paḥtu</foreign> will disappear, the long <foreign xml:lang="ta">ū</foreign>-sound</l>
<l>must be inserted, [and] the consonant <foreign xml:lang="ta">t</foreign> will be replaced by <foreign xml:lang="ta">ṟ.</foreign><note place="foot">The form <foreign xml:lang="ta">toṇṇūṟu</foreign> ' ninety ' is explained
          purely synchronically by the following ordered process : <foreign xml:lang="ta">oṉpatu +
          pattu &gt; * oṉpapahtu</foreign> (accord. to aphorism 438) &gt; <foreign xml:lang="ta">*
          toṇpatupahṯu &gt; * toṇṇapapahtu &gt; * toṇṇutu &gt; toṇṇūṟu.</foreign> Cf. also Comment
          on Chapter 8.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
